  abstract: (
    content: [
      三维重建是计算机视觉、计算机图形学和机器人感知中的重要研究方向，在数字孪生、虚拟现实、工业检测、文物保护和自动化扫描等场景中具有广泛应用。近年来，神经辐射场和三维高斯泼溅等神经渲染表示显著提升了新视角合成和可渲染三维重建质量，但实际重建效果仍高度依赖输入视角的覆盖范围和采集质量。在稀疏视角条件下，物体背面、遮挡区域、复杂材质和远处背景容易出现模糊、重影、结构断裂和颜色漂移等问题。传统均匀采样或人工规划方式往往会引入冗余视角，难以在有限采集预算和机器人运动约束下稳定获得高质量重建结果。因此，如何根据当前重建状态自动选择最有价值的下一视角，是主动三维重建中的关键问题。

      针对上述问题，本文研究了一种基于数据驱动不确定性的主动三维重建方法。本文以三维高斯表示作为重建基础，将主动重建组织为“初始视角采样、三维高斯重建、候选视角渲染、不确定性评估、下一视角采集、模型继续优化”的闭环流程。在每一轮主动选择中，系统首先利用已有视角训练当前三维高斯模型，然后在候选视角下渲染颜色图和深度图，并通过不确定性模型预测候选视角中可能存在的重建薄弱区域，最终选择综合不确定性最高的视角加入训练集合。与仅依赖几何覆盖、Fisher 信息或二维图像质量的视角选择方法不同，本文方法同时利用颜色图中的外观伪影和深度图中的几何不稳定信息，使候选视角评分能够更直接地反映当前模型的真实重建误差。

      在方法设计上，本文构建了颜色与深度联合的不确定性评估模型。颜色图分支用于预测纹理模糊、颜色漂移、重影和反光异常等外观不确定性，深度图分支用于刻画表面断裂、遮挡边界不稳定和空间层次错误等几何不确定性。为避免单一模态估计带来的偏差，本文进一步设计深度感知融合和深度不确定性重加权策略，将颜色不确定性、深度值和深度可靠性统一为候选视角综合评分。训练阶段，本文利用多视角对象和真实场景数据构造稀疏视角三维高斯重建样本，并通过保留视角渲染结果与真实图像之间的结构相似性误差自动生成像素级不确定性标签，从而避免人工标注不确定区域。

      实验部分从对象级重建、复杂材质对象、场景级重建和真实机器人扫描等方面验证了本文方法的有效性。结果表明，在对象级主动重建任务中，本文方法在平均 PSNR、SSIM、LPIPS 以及最差视角质量上均优于随机选择、图像质量评价方法和信息论方法；在复杂材质对象和 Mip-NeRF360 场景中，本文方法也能保持较好的泛化能力，并减少局部严重失败。消融实验表明，深度感知融合和深度不确定性重加权均对视角选择性能有明显贡献。真实机器人扫描实验进一步说明，数据驱动不确定性评分能够迁移到机械臂采集流程中，为自动化三维扫描提供有效的下一视角和扫描路径决策依据。
    ],
    keywords: ("主动三维重建", "数据驱动不确定性", "三维高斯泼溅", "下一最佳视角", "机器人扫描"),
  ),
  abstract-en: (
    content: [
      Three-dimensional reconstruction is an important research topic in computer vision, computer graphics, and robotic perception, with broad applications in digital twins, virtual reality, industrial inspection, cultural heritage preservation, and automated scanning. Recent neural rendering representations, such as Neural Radiance Fields and 3D Gaussian Splatting, have greatly improved novel view synthesis and renderable 3D reconstruction. However, the reconstruction quality still strongly depends on the coverage and quality of input views. Under sparse-view conditions, occluded regions, back-side surfaces, complex materials, and distant backgrounds often suffer from blur, ghosting artifacts, structural discontinuities, and color drift. Uniform sampling and manually designed capture trajectories usually introduce redundant views and are difficult to use under limited acquisition budgets and robotic motion constraints. Therefore, selecting the most informative next view according to the current reconstruction state is a key problem in active 3D reconstruction.

      To address this problem, this thesis studies an active 3D reconstruction method based on data-driven uncertainty. The proposed system uses 3D Gaussian representation as the reconstruction backbone and organizes active reconstruction as a closed loop of initial view sampling, 3D Gaussian reconstruction, candidate-view rendering, uncertainty estimation, next-view acquisition, and continued model optimization. At each active selection round, the system first trains the current 3D Gaussian model from the acquired views, renders color and depth maps for candidate views, predicts potentially unreliable regions using an uncertainty model, and then adds the candidate view with the highest overall uncertainty score into the training set. Different from view selection methods based only on geometric coverage, Fisher information, or two-dimensional image quality, the proposed method jointly exploits appearance artifacts in rendered color images and geometric instability in rendered depth maps, making the candidate-view score more directly related to the actual reconstruction error of the current model.

      In terms of methodology, this thesis designs a joint color-depth uncertainty estimation model. The color branch predicts appearance uncertainty caused by texture blur, color drift, ghosting, and specular artifacts, while the depth branch captures geometric uncertainty caused by surface discontinuities, unstable occlusion boundaries, and incorrect spatial ordering. To reduce the bias of single-modality estimation, a depth-aware fusion strategy and a depth-uncertainty reweighting strategy are further introduced, combining color uncertainty, depth values, and depth reliability into a unified candidate-view score. During training, sparse-view 3D Gaussian reconstruction samples are constructed from multi-view object data and real-scene data. Pixel-level uncertainty labels are automatically generated by measuring structural similarity errors between held-out rendered images and ground-truth images, avoiding manual annotation of uncertain regions.

      Experiments are conducted on object-level reconstruction, complex material objects, scene-level reconstruction, and real robotic scanning. The results show that, on object-level active reconstruction, the proposed method outperforms random selection, image-quality-based methods, and information-theoretic methods in average PSNR, SSIM, LPIPS, and worst-view quality. On complex material objects and Mip-NeRF360 scenes, the method also maintains good generalization ability and reduces severe local failures. Ablation studies demonstrate that both depth-aware fusion and depth-uncertainty reweighting contribute clearly to view selection performance. Real robotic scanning experiments further show that data-driven uncertainty scoring can be transferred to a robotic acquisition pipeline, providing effective decision support for next-view selection and scanning-path planning in automated 3D reconstruction.
    ],
    keywords: ("active 3D reconstruction", "data-driven uncertainty", "3D Gaussian Splatting", "next-best-view", "robotic scanning"),
  ),
